show_histograms(data_dropDate)

In this case, histogram will show us variable range and distribution. We can see that palm oil planted in tropical area from temperature distribution. We can also see that farmers work 24-26 days in a month and can harvest 750 - 840 hectares in a month. FFB produced around 1 - 2.2 Tonnes/Hectare in a month.

Time Series Plot

show_time_series_plot(data)

Seasonal Plot

In [12]:
show_seasonal_plot(data)

As I suspected, there is seasonal pattern here !

  • Harvesting activity increased in first semester and then decrese in second semester
  • FFB yields increased in the second half as rainfall (precipitation) increased
  • Precipitation seems affect both soil moisture (Positive Correlation) and average temperature (Negative Correlation)
  • Working days are fluctuates around 25 days

Remove Outliers

In [21]:
data_outliers_dates = data_outliers["Date"].to_list()
data_no_outliers = data.copy()
data_no_outliers = data_no_outliers[~data_no_outliers["Date"].isin(data_outliers_dates)]

Regression and Variable Importance

In this case, regression is used to find significant variable.

In [22]:
# Set Target/Response/Dependent Variable as "FFB_Yield"
y_train = data_no_outliers["FFB_Yield"].copy()
y_test = data["FFB_Yield"].copy()

First Linear Model

Try a Simple Model First :)

In [23]:
# Select some Features for Linear Model

# Drop "Date" and "month" Columns and also "FFB_Yield" 
# Don't forget to drop "Max_Temp" that have high correlation value with "Average_Temp"

x_train1 = data_no_outliers.copy()
x_train1 = x_train1.drop(["Date","month","FFB_Yield","Max_Temp"], axis=1)

x_test1 = data.copy()
x_test1 = x_test1.drop(["Date","month","FFB_Yield","Max_Temp"], axis=1)

# adding a constant
x_train1 = sm.add_constant(x_train1) 
x_test1 = sm.add_constant(x_test1)
In [24]:
# Create First Linear Model
model_lin1 = sm.OLS(y_train, x_train1).fit()
print(model_lin1.summary())

Random Forest Model

Random Forest is a Non-Parametric Model and suitable for non-linear data

In [33]:
# Pick only significant variables
x_train3 = data_no_outliers.copy()
x_train3 = x_train3[["SoilMoisture", "Precipitation","HA_Harvested"]]

x_test3 = data.copy()
x_test3 = x_test3[["SoilMoisture", "Precipitation","HA_Harvested"]]

We can see the order of significant variables here.
First is "HA_Harvested", followed by "Precipitation", and the last is "SoilMoisture"

Additional Notes
We have identified three significant variables ("HA_Harvested", "Precipitation", "SoilMoisture").
Keep in mind that regression is used to find those variables.
The main purpose is to find those variables, not to predict "FFB Yield" accurately/robustly.
Reproducing a robust model will required Cross-Validation technique.
